<text>Potential Energy in Covalent Bond Formation: Reacting Two Oxygen Atoms

When covalent bonds form, much of the chemical potential energy is converted to kinetic energy. Because the covalent bond is much stronger and more stable than the van der Waals attractions, more chemical potential energy can be converted to kinetic energy than happens during phase changes when molecules form weak van der Waals attractions. Press the run button to see this reaction.

 
      

 

